Using remote sensing to map invasive species

Success in the strategies to manage biological invasions relies on the ability to detect and monitor species distributions. However, field surveys devoted to detect and map invasive species are time consuming and might lead to observational bias, e.g.decreased sampling effort at less accesible areas.

Remote sensing provides a large-scale standardized spatially and temporally explicit data to map and monitor the distribution of invasive species. Here, as part of the DIARS project, we present a method to map invasive species using hyperspectral images.

The dataset

In this tutorial we will map the distribution of a invasive bryophyte species (Campylopus introflexus) in an already prepared artificial image. You can download the dataset for this tutorial from HERE. These dataset includes: the hyperspectral image (tif file) and a set of calibration, validation and background points containing ground measurements that will be use to develop the species distribution map.

The framework

Figure 1. Framework used to map invasive secies distribution using remote sensing.

Setting the R environment

Lets start by loading the libraries that we are going to be using in this tutorial. To load the packages, it is necessary to first install them using the command install.packages(c("raster","rgdal","hyperSpec","rgeos","rgrass7")).

library(raster)
library(rgdal)
library(hyperSpec)
library(rgeos)
library(rgrass7)

It is recommended to first create a folder where the datasets (tif file and point files, download a sample dataset from HERE) are located and the outputs and results will be saved. To set the working directory in R to the folder created:

setwd("/home/garzonc/Desktop/DIARS")

Data preparation

Field data

To extract the spectral values for calibration, validation and background points: load the hyperspectral image in R and plot it using one of the bands

filelist <- dir(pattern = ".tiff")
mos <- raster(filelist[2], band = 150)

layers <- stack(list.files(".", "asc", full.names = TRUE))
plot(mos)

To read the point shapefiles make sure they are located in the current working folder. Initiate the GRASS software from within R, set the projection, region and resolution:

# dir.create('grassdata')

myGRASS <- "/usr/local/grass-7.0.4svn"
myGISDbase <- "/home/garzonc/Documents/grassData"
myLocation <- "DIARS"
myMapset <- "PERMANENT"

initGRASS(myGRASS, home = tempdir(), gisDbase = myGISDbase, location = myLocation, 
    mapset = myMapset, override = TRUE)

Is important to also extract the values for an area around the point (buffer area), in this case of the size of the field plots. So we have to create a buffer around calibration points and save it as a shapefile:

dataBuffer <- gBuffer(pointdata_cal, byid = T, width = 3, capStyle = "SQUARE")

plot(layers[[150]])
points(pointdata_cal, pch = 3, cex = 0.3)
plot(dataBuffer, add = TRUE)

# shapefile(dataBuffer, 'CalibBuffer3m.shp', overwrite=TRUE)

Create a table with only the coordinates (x,y)

pointdataXY_calB <- pointdata_cal@data[, 3:4]

And extract and calculate the mean value in each buffer area and for each band. Then, add the type column and joint the coordinates, column and row names to the dataframe with the values extracted for each band. Preview the resulting table and save it as a csv file.

pixvals <- extract(layers, dataBuffer, method = "simple", small = T, weights = T, 
    fun = mean)

# sort band columns in ascending order and name colummns an rows
pixExtract <- pixvals[, paste("X", seq(1:248), sep = "")]
type <- rep("Calibration", 90)
calXY_pix <- cbind(type, pointdata_cal@data[, 3:5], pixExtract)
rownames(calXY_pix) <- pointdata_cal@data$cat
# head(calXY_pix) #Run this line to preview the first 5 rows of the table
write.table(calXY_pix, "PointCalib.csv", quote = F)

Finally, the extraction of the spectral values for the background points. Note that the background points must be carefully selected to reduce or avoid the seleting of false absences (see Lobo et al. 2010 on the selection of pseudoabsences). You can read more on the procedure followed to select pseudoabsences for the study species mapped in this tutorial in Skowronek et al. 2016 (in press).

Then, add the type column and the coordinates to the dataframe with the values extracted for each band and at each point (there are in total 1000 background points). Preview the resulting table and save it as a csv file.

Remote sensing data

Hyperspectral images provide many advantages due to the large amount of information contain in each pixel (in this case 248 bands) but this also posits limitations in time and processing power. One of the techniques most commonly used to reduce the dimension of the data, without loosing relevant information, is the Principal Components Analysis (PCA).

library(raster)
library(rgdal)
library(foreach)

Import the point dataset. Lets used the calibration and background points for this analysis.

plots <- read.table("PointCalib.csv", header = T, sep = " ")[, -c(2:4)]
Background <- read.table("PointBackground.csv", header = T, sep = " ")

spec <- rbind(plots, Background)

library(reshape2)
library(ggplot2)
sample <- melt(spec, id = c("type"))

p <- ggplot(sample, aes(sample[, 2], sample[, 3])) + geom_boxplot(aes(fill = sample[, 
    2]), outlier.colour = NULL) + theme(axis.text.x = element_text(angle = 90, 
    hjust = 0), axis.title = element_text(face = "bold", size = 14), title = element_text(face = "bold", 
    size = 16), legend.position = "none") + labs(title = paste("Spectral response"), 
    x = "Wavelength, nm", y = "Response")
p

Calculate the first component

plots <- as.matrix(read.table("PointCalib.csv", header = T, sep = " ")[, -c(1:4)])
Background <- as.matrix(read.table("PointBackground.csv", header = T, sep = " ")[, 
    -c(1)])


spec1 <- rbind(plots, Background)

pca <- prcomp(spec1, scale. = T, center = T)

pca_red <- prcomp(spec1, scale. = T, center = T, tol = 0.01)  # Calculate only first components, tol=0 or tol = 
pca_red$sdev[1:11]

Maxent modelling

Before starting running any script, it is important to download Maxent from the website https://www.cs.princeton.edu/~schapire/maxent/) and copy the file maxent.jarand paste it in the folder called java of the dismo package file.

library(dismo)
library(rJava)

setwd("/home/garzonc/Desktop/DIARS")

Load the tables with the previously extracted values for the buffer areas around the calibration points, and used the vector cal_points to select the plots with >0 species coverage values (cam_cover column). Joint the presences table with the background table, and in the resulting table omit the x and y coordinate and type columns and only keep the spectral values. Finally create a vector y with 1 and 0 values corresponding to the presences (1) and background (0) rows.

occs <- read.table("PointCalib.csv", header = T, sep = " ")

occsPRES <- subset(occs, occs$cam_cover > 0)
occsABS <- subset(occs, occs$cam_cover < 0.1)


occsPRES <- occsPRES[, -c(1:4)]
occsABS <- occsABS[, -c(1:4)]

Background <- read.table("PointBackground.csv", header = T, sep = " ")[, -c(1)]
names(occsPRES) <- names(Background)
specs <- rbind(occsPRES, occsABS, Background)
specs <- specs[, -c(1:3)]
specs <- specs[, -c(1, 2, 146:157, 194:220)]
y <- c(rep(1, nrow(occsPRES)), rep(0, nrow(occsABS)), rep(0, nrow(Background)))

After preparing the data tables you can run the model, generate the predictions and the probabilities map.

library(dismo)
me <- maxent(specs, y, args = c("addsamplestobackground=true", "applyThresholdRule=10 percentile training presence"), 
    path = "./outputR")

pred <- predict(me, layers, progress = "text")
## 
  |                                                                       
  |                                                                 |   0%
  |                                                                       
  |================                                                 |  25%
  |                                                                       
  |================================                                 |  50%
  |                                                                       
  |=================================================                |  75%
  |                                                                       
  |=================================================================| 100%
## 
plot(pred)

writeRaster(pred, "./outputR/map.tif", overwrite = T)
save(me, file = "./outputR/mx_obj.RData")
You can explore the AUC curve and values from the maxent model by opening the html file stored in the ./outputR1 folder.

Model validation

For the validation process, load the table with the spectral values of the validation points buffer areas (prevously created), divide the table in presences and absences to create the vector of 0 and 1 values (y), create a vector y with 1 and 0 values corresponding to the presences (1) and absences (0) rows and joint it all in one table.

occval <- read.table("PointValid.csv", header = T, sep = " ")
occsP <- subset(occval, occval$cam_cover > 0)  #presences
occsA <- subset(occval, occval$cam_cover < 0.1)  #absences

y <- c(rep(1, nrow(occsP)), rep(0, nrow(occsA)))

specsVal <- rbind(occsP, occsA)
specsVAL <- specsVal[, -c(1:4)]
specsVAL <- specsVAL[, -c(1, 2, 146:157, 194:220)]

The validation table just created is used in the evaluate function to evaluate the model previously constructed. The resulting evaluation contains the outcomes of the model cross-validation, such as the True Skill Statistic (TSS) and ROC curves. Additionally, the threshold function allows selection the threshold value where the sum of the sensitivity and specificity values is the highest. This value can also be used to generate the presence map based on the model prediction.

e <- evaluate(model = me, p = occsP, a = occsA)
par(mfrow = c(1, 2))
tss <- e@TPR + e@TNR - 1
plot(e@t, tss, type = "l", xlab = "Thresholds", ylab = "TSS", main = "TSS")
e@t[which.max(tss)]
## [1] 0.2170566
plot(e, "ROC")

Distribution map

Now we can generate a presence map using the threshold value that maximizes the kappa value:

par(mfrow = c(1, 1))
tr <- threshold(e, "spec_sens")
plot(pred > tr, main = "Presence Locations and Prediction (Reduced Model)")

# See all the outcomes of the model evaluation
str(e)
